726262f-d.title: Queens: Broadway - 51st Avenue
726262f-d.text:
Broadway (tracks thereon) east side, north from 51st Avenue
(formerly Aaurice Avenue, also known as Cook Avenue) to Corona
Avenue (formerly Union Avenue); showing at the corncr foreground,
the C. Cook residence of 1873 (formcrly 56 Broadway). One Douglas
wS the owner in 1891. John A. Rapelje's real estate office was
located here in 1822. The houses beyond it occupy the site of the
old Newtown House an old tire tavern. This site was eventually
owned by the lst Reformed Church of Newtown. The Ne.town Hotel
of later days stood on the opiuositc side of the street. Pn views 2,3,
and 4 is seen the 1st Dutch Reforred Church of Newtowm. Te Dutch
Ch rch Mas built on land donated April S, 1733. ine first edifice
was erected in 1735 and was 7O60 ft. It Mas demolished on Sept. 4, 1831.
Abraham Riker and his brother-in-law P. Rapelje gave the land for
a church and burial around to the village of Newtown. The corner
stone for the second edifice was laid on Sept. 16, 1831 by Elder
Francis Durvea, and the edifice wad dedicated July 29th, 1832 by
the Rev. Schoonaker D.D. Thhe bell used in this church was cast in
Araterdam in 1792. The chapel adjoininm the chirch as erected in
1854.

Droadway at the S.W. corner of Maeoiot Avenue, showiug
for views of the former St. Jares Epiucopal Church. It was
erected ahout 1735. Pews were installed ir 1740. In 1760
the edifice was repaired and the 9teeple rebuilt. IIt was en-
larged about 177O and again repaired about 1816. In 1922
it was pairted. The last services in this structure were held
on July 16, 1848 when the new edifice was dedicated for service.
Thia place has since been used as a chapel. The steeple was
removed about 1900. A small buryirg ground is located in the
rear of this chapel. The Rev. Evar Malhone Johnson, b 1792,

726263f-a.title: Queens: Broadway - 51st Avenue
726263f-a.text:
Broadway, south from 51st Avenue. On the extreme right is a
portion of St. James Protestant Episcopal Chapel and beyond it is
a local firehouse (building with bell tower). On the left is the
cylindrical-turreted 110th Police Precinct and courthouse, formerly
the Town Hall, built in 1891. The building with the watch tower
was known as the Walter Building, havng been owned by one Schneller
1n 1891.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection  1922
MAY BE REPRODUCED

726266f-a.title: Queens: Broadway - 51st Avenue
726266f-a.text:
Broadway, at the S.W. corner of 51st Avenue, showing the
original St. James Protestant Episcopal Church, built in 1735,
and now (1941) known as the Parish Hall of St. James P.E. Church.
Mr. Ogden states that the Newtown Historical Society, of whose
council Dr. Paltsits,former head of the American History Division
of the New York Public Library is a member, was organized in the
summer of 1941, in this building.
Views 1 and 2 show the rear of the place, on 51st Avenue, and
view 3 the front, on Broadway. The new St. James Church is at the
N.E. corner of Broadway and Corona Avenue.
View 1:  Eugene L. Armbruster Collection March, 1925
MAY BE REPRODUCED
View 2:  P. L. Sperr  July 2, 1935
NO REPRODUCTIONS
View 3:  Gift of Beecher Ogden  July, 1941
NO REPRODUCTIONS
